HEADWORD: Refection
<hw>Re*fec"tion</hw> <pr>(r?*f?k"sh?n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>refectio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>r⟦eacute⟧fection</ets>. See
<er>Refect</er>, <er>Fact</er>.]</ety> <def>Refreshment after hunger or
fatigue; a repast; a lunch.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[His] feeble spirit inly felt <qex>refection</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those Attic nights, and those <qex>refections</qex> of the
gods.</q> <rj><qau>Curran.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Refective</ent>⟦br⟧
